00:43:57.282 --> 00:44:01.182
these curves. So certainly, a potentially promising

727
00:44:01.202 --> 00:44:04.802
therapy for this challenging group of patients

728
00:44:05.222 --> 00:44:08.842
that deserves further study.

729
00:44:09.782 --> 00:44:13.222
There's also been some interesting work in using GD2-directed CARs for diffuse

730
00:44:13.302 --> 00:44:16.722
midline glioma. This is a phase 1 trial

731
00:44:17.622 --> 00:44:17.932
that

732
00:44:19.182 --> 00:44:22.842
was conducted with a second generation CAR, where they reported three out of four

733
00:44:22.882 --> 00:44:26.522
patients had a radiographic response in these

734
00:44:26.722 --> 00:44:30.402
H3K27 mutated diffuse midline gliomas, although the

735
00:44:30.422 --> 00:44:34.362
responses were relatively short-lived, with all of the patients passing away

736
00:44:34.402 --> 00:44:36.102
from disease within a year of treatment.

737
00:44:38.202 --> 00:44:41.342
And to address this, they have followed this up with

738
00:44:41.422 --> 00:44:45.342
a trial using armored CAR, where

739
00:44:45.402 --> 00:44:48.482
you use an IL-7 receptor to try to increase

740
00:44:49.162 --> 00:44:52.582
persistence of the CAR, and reported that seven out of eight

741
00:44:52.662 --> 00:44:55.922
patients had at least stable disease,

742
00:44:56.542 --> 00:45:00.162
and some neurologic improvement that lasted an average of five months.

743
00:45:02.642 --> 00:45:03.782
There's been a number of other

744
00:45:05.042 --> 00:45:08.902
studies trying to further improve efficacy of CAR T cells

745
00:45:08.942 --> 00:45:10.342
for pediatric solid tumors.

746
00:45:11.242 --> 00:45:14.922
This, that I'm highlighting here, is a trial of IL-15 armored

747
00:45:14.982 --> 00:45:18.702
GPC3 CAR T cells that's expressed on a number of different

748
00:45:18.762 --> 00:45:22.342
tumors, including hepatocellular carcinoma, which is a

749
00:45:22.382 --> 00:45:26.302
pediatric and adult cancer, but also hepatoblastoma, a cancer

750
00:45:26.342 --> 00:45:28.562
that occurs in very young children.

751
00:45:29.642 --> 00:45:33.242
Again, expressing IL-15 to try to promote CAR T cell expansion,

752
00:45:33.662 --> 00:45:37.582
and reporting that with the combination of these two, they saw

753
00:45:37.742 --> 00:45:40.762
responses in 33%, four out of 12 patients.

754
00:45:42.382 --> 00:45:44.282
But these were, again, relatively short-lived.

755
00:45:44.342 --> 00:45:48.132
So I think what I'm trying to highlight here is that there are some exciting

756
00:45:48.182 --> 00:45:51.962
results in solid tumor CARs, but they're also certainly not of the same

757
00:45:52.562 --> 00:45:55.162
magnitude that we've seen in the leukemia space to date.

758
00:45:55.942 --> 00:45:59.672
And so, certainly deserve further work and

759
00:45:59.682 --> 00:46:03.482
preclinical and clinical investigation to figure out if this is a

760
00:46:03.522 --> 00:46:05.562
path forward for this group of patients.

761
00:46:08.102 --> 00:46:11.942
As I highlighted, there's a number of different of these CAR T cells under

762
00:46:11.962 --> 00:46:15.842
development. This is not an exhaustive list, but just a number of trials that are

763
00:46:15.902 --> 00:46:19.442
ongoing at multiple institutions of different CARs against different

764
00:46:19.482 --> 00:46:22.842
targets for leukemia, including B and T cell

765
00:46:23.362 --> 00:46:26.982
ALL, as well as AML, for a variety of solid tumors,

766
00:46:28.242 --> 00:46:31.392
and for brain tumors. And so I think it's really been an exciting time where

767
00:46:31.402 --> 00:46:33.342
there's been a lot of these clinical trials.

768
00:46:34.242 --> 00:46:37.962
But with a few exceptions, and there are exceptions, most of these are

769
00:46:38.042 --> 00:46:40.802
academic studies conducted at a single institution.

770
00:46:41.422 --> 00:46:44.842
And so it does pose questions as to how we're going to

771
00:46:45.382 --> 00:46:46.962
move this forward in the future.

772
00:46:50.082 --> 00:46:50.302
So,

773
00:46:51.302 --> 00:46:54.942
with the last few minutes, I'd like to talk about the destination and

774
00:46:55.362 --> 00:46:59.182
is FDA approval the goal? Certainly, that has been expressed as the

775
00:46:59.222 --> 00:47:03.002
goal for small molecules, and if it is the goal, why have approvals been so

776
00:47:03.082 --> 00:47:04.282
limited in this space?

777
00:47:06.182 --> 00:47:09.942
And I think the underlying problem is what you've

778
00:47:09.982 --> 00:47:13.182
heard throughout, is that there's limited investment in

779
00:47:13.262 --> 00:47:16.562
these trials because they are

780
00:47:16.642 --> 00:47:18.522
expensive and have a small market.

781
00:47:19.502 --> 00:47:23.082
And I would argue that we don't necessarily need FDA

782
00:47:23.142 --> 00:47:26.642
approval of these therapies in the same way that we do of small

783
00:47:26.702 --> 00:47:29.862
molecules or other biologics, because

784
00:47:30.202 --> 00:47:33.772
uniquely, CAR T cells can be manufactured in the academic setting, and

785
00:47:33.802 --> 00:47:37.382
that's essentially unique to all of the other types of therapies that we're talking

786
00:47:37.442 --> 00:47:41.182
about, whether antibody drug conjugates, bispecific antibodies, or small molecules.

787
00:47:41.682 --> 00:47:45.282
All of those essentially will require a manufacturer.

788
00:47:45.342 --> 00:47:48.722
In this case, individual institutions can manufacture this at

789
00:47:48.782 --> 00:47:52.462
relatively reasonable costs of about $50,000 per patient

790
00:47:52.522 --> 00:47:56.342
manufacturing cost, which is significantly less actually than the costs

791
00:47:56.351 --> 00:47:59.382
that we are charged for commercial CAR T cells.

792
00:48:00.322 --> 00:48:02.722
I think there are certainly challenges with this approach, though, right?

793
00:48:02.862 --> 00:48:06.602
So I highlighted some exciting results from GD2 CAR T cell trials,

794
00:48:06.942 --> 00:48:10.282
but there's been a large range of these trials, and the results are very variable,

795
00:48:10.662 --> 00:48:13.862
and there's differences in the constructs, there's differences in the manufacturing

796
00:48:13.902 --> 00:48:17.752
process. And so if we have individual academic centers

797
00:48:17.842 --> 00:48:21.742
each manufacturing their own product, how do we ensure that those are consistent

798
00:48:21.782 --> 00:48:25.402
and functional, and that the patients are getting the best therapy for their

799
00:48:25.422 --> 00:48:25.982
disease,

800
00:48:26.902 --> 00:48:30.782
when we don't have comparative trials, and we don't have

801
00:48:30.822 --> 00:48:34.362
the consistency that's achieved with FDA approval and a standard

802
00:48:34.862 --> 00:48:38.662
manufacturing process? And I think, of course, I've focused

803
00:48:38.702 --> 00:48:42.442
primarily on the United States, but this is even more challenging to scale

804
00:48:42.482 --> 00:48:43.442
globally,

805
00:48:44.702 --> 00:48:48.382
where many centers may lack the resources to deploy these

806
00:48:48.422 --> 00:48:49.842
therapies for their patients.

807
00:48:50.842 --> 00:48:54.832
And I would, again, say that I spoke most about CAR T cells today, but I

808
00:48:54.842 --> 00:48:58.652
think lack of FDA approval is a more challenging problem for bispecific

809
00:48:58.702 --> 00:49:01.982
antibodies that are generally not going to be manufactured in the academic setting.

810
00:49:02.022 --> 00:49:05.042
And so these generally follow the paradigm that you heard from Dr.

811
00:49:05.262 --> 00:49:09.142
Fox earlier about needing to expand what's being

812
00:49:09.182 --> 00:49:10.922
done for adult patients to

813
00:49:10.962 --> 00:49:14.858
pediatrics.I'd also

814
00:49:14.878 --> 00:49:18.318
like to just talk for a minute about, um, repurposing adult

815
00:49:18.378 --> 00:49:21.978
therapies within this space, which I think is somewhat more challenging than you

816
00:49:21.998 --> 00:49:25.678
think about for small molecules. Um, if you look back to Dr.

817
00:49:25.898 --> 00:49:29.778
Fox's talk, a number of the agents that were approved are small molecules

818
00:49:29.818 --> 00:49:33.438
that have received histology agnostic indications based on a genomic

819
00:49:33.478 --> 00:49:37.438
biomarker. Um, so that's certainly true for the ertrectinib that she mentioned.

820
00:49:37.568 --> 00:49:41.138
Also, some of the immunotherapies, um, uh, like the anti-PD-1

821
00:49:41.238 --> 00:49:45.178
therapies, um, have all received histology agnostic indications that included

822
00:49:45.218 --> 00:49:48.798
children and then could be done in a relatively small pediatric patient

823
00:49:48.858 --> 00:49:51.718
population, not having to focus on a specific histology.

824
00:49:52.298 --> 00:49:55.558
But I think that's harder in these, uh, therapies that are based on expression

825
00:49:55.618 --> 00:49:57.638
rather than based on genomic biomarkers.

826
00:49:58.118 --> 00:50:01.458
Um, some of these therapies do not have a formal companion

827
00:50:01.518 --> 00:50:05.258
diagnostic like blinatumomab or tisagenlecleucel, although institutions

828
00:50:05.278 --> 00:50:09.098
routinely assess CD19 expression by flow

829
00:50:09.118 --> 00:50:12.958
cytometry, but others do. So afamelcel, which is a

830
00:50:13.018 --> 00:50:16.758
T-cell receptor therapy, um, that's approved for patients with synovial

831
00:50:16.778 --> 00:50:20.278
sarcoma, requires positive immunohistochemistry for

832
00:50:20.298 --> 00:50:24.218
MAYJ4. Um, but these assays are typically only validated in the disease

833
00:50:24.278 --> 00:50:27.958
of interest, in this case, synovial sarcoma, um, and have not been, uh,

834
00:50:28.138 --> 00:50:31.478
studied, um, in across, uh, histologies. And as Dr.

835
00:50:31.698 --> 00:50:35.618
Fox mentioned with the trastuzumab example, it can be really hard

836
00:50:35.678 --> 00:50:39.088
to move these antibodies across different therapies in a way that are not

837
00:50:39.138 --> 00:50:43.058
true when you're using a sequencing-based assay looking for a genomic fusion

838
00:50:43.118 --> 00:50:46.438
or a point mutation, which generally can be applied regardless of

839
00:50:46.478 --> 00:50:47.248
histology.

840
00:50:48.478 --> 00:50:52.288
We certainly can think about other methods like RNA-seq, but, um, these don't

841
00:50:52.338 --> 00:50:56.178
assess the actual expression or translation of the protein and are

842
00:50:56.258 --> 00:51:00.218
not typically what's being validated for, um, the companion diagnostic

843
00:51:00.238 --> 00:51:02.318
for these therapies in adults.

844
00:51:03.698 --> 00:51:06.038
And I just highlight a couple of examples where this is, um,

845
00:51:06.858 --> 00:51:10.738
being studied. Um, so this is a pediatric trial of

846
00:51:10.758 --> 00:51:14.498
afamelcel, which as I mentioned, is a T-cell receptor, uh, therapy against

847
00:51:14.558 --> 00:51:18.378
MAYJ4, um, that demonstrated a forty-three percent response rate

848
00:51:18.438 --> 00:51:22.218
in adults with synovial sarcoma, um, and is now being

849
00:51:22.278 --> 00:51:24.748
studied in the pediatric population.

850
00:51:24.877 --> 00:51:28.198
Um, this trial was initially accruing children with a number of different diseases

851
00:51:28.238 --> 00:51:31.418
and now has been restricted to patients just with synovial sarcoma,

852
00:51:31.898 --> 00:51:35.618
um, uh, to just evaluate that patient population, so

853
00:51:35.698 --> 00:51:38.458
limiting the number of pediatric patients who will be included.

854
00:51:40.658 --> 00:51:44.558
And then I would just highlight one other, um, example, um, where there

855
00:51:44.598 --> 00:51:47.458
were some more challenges, which is, um, tarlatamab, which is a

856
00:51:47.498 --> 00:51:51.478
DLL3/CD3 bispecific antibody, um, that has, um,

857
00:51:51.538 --> 00:51:54.758
had a significant impact in the treatment of adults with small cell lung cancer,

858
00:51:55.167 --> 00:51:59.078
um, where in a randomized trial, it demonstrated a higher response rate as well

859
00:51:59.138 --> 00:52:02.338
as improvements in progression-free survival and overall survival.

860
00:52:03.198 --> 00:52:06.258
Um, DLL3 is expressed in neuroblastoma.

861
00:52:06.318 --> 00:52:10.118
There was a paper published several years ago, uh, demonstrating that in a

862
00:52:10.158 --> 00:52:12.978
subset of neuroblastomas, DLL3 is expressed and that a

863
00:52:13.018 --> 00:52:16.918
DLL3, um, antibody drug conjugate was active in preclinical

864
00:52:16.978 --> 00:52:20.298
models. Um, but tarlatamab was not studied in children.

865
00:52:20.338 --> 00:52:20.958
It was, um,

866
00:52:21.778 --> 00:52:25.447
at the time on the FDA-relevant target list, and so it was granted a

867
00:52:25.498 --> 00:52:29.447
waiver. That waiver has since been removed, but the drug has now been approved,

868
00:52:29.498 --> 00:52:32.798
and so there's no longer a requirement to study the specific drug in pediatric

869
00:52:32.858 --> 00:52:34.638
patients that may apply to future drugs.

870
00:52:35.138 --> 00:52:38.568
And I just highlight, this is actually one of my patients where, um,

871
00:52:38.978 --> 00:52:41.338
that this drug may be applicable to pediatric patients.

872
00:52:41.398 --> 00:52:45.018
This is a patient of mine who had a chemotherapy refractory high-grade

873
00:52:45.038 --> 00:52:48.788
neuroendocrine tumor, um, who received this therapy, um, off-label and

874
00:52:49.158 --> 00:52:51.798
has an ongoing metabolic complete response.

875
00:52:52.238 --> 00:52:55.918
So some of these, uh, rare therapies do need to be studied in children, and we need

876
00:52:55.938 --> 00:52:59.918
to think about how do we assess expression of these targets in children, um, more

877
00:52:59.938 --> 00:53:03.878
broadly and across histologies to make sure that, um, these therapies

878
00:53:03.958 --> 00:53:05.658
can move to our pediatric patients.

879
00:53:07.238 --> 00:53:10.918
Um, so with that, uh, I hope I've talked a little bit about, um, my perspective on

880
00:53:11.078 --> 00:53:14.958
lessons learned of a decade of bispecific and CAR therapies, um, for children

881
00:53:14.998 --> 00:53:18.848
with cancer and really highlighted the sort of revolutionary, uh,

882
00:53:19.038 --> 00:53:23.018
impact of blinatumomab and tisagenlecleucel for children with B-ALL,

883
00:53:23.418 --> 00:53:27.358
and how we've seen, um, promise of other CAR T-cells primarily

884
00:53:27.378 --> 00:53:29.758
in hematologic malignancies, but also in solid tumors.

885
00:53:29.778 --> 00:53:33.768
But very limited, um, commercial development in this space, uh,

886
00:53:33.778 --> 00:53:37.658
despite the substantial academic interest and number of trials that are being

887
00:53:37.698 --> 00:53:41.418
conducted. Um, and highlight a little bit the potential to

888
00:53:41.438 --> 00:53:45.367
leverage products primarily developed for adults, but the need to think about

889
00:53:45.418 --> 00:53:48.778
how do we systematically assess these targets in pediatric

890
00:53:48.788 --> 00:53:52.268
cancer in a way that we, I would argue, have not yet done.

891
00:53:52.358 --> 00:53:52.458
Um,

892
00:53:53.818 --> 00:53:56.538
we've done this for genomic targets, but not necessarily for all these

893
00:53:56.578 --> 00:53:58.458
expression-based targets in pediatric cancer.

894
00:53:59.698 --> 00:54:02.058
Uh, again, thank you very much for your attention, and thank you again for the

895
00:54:02.078 --> 00:54:02.758
invitation to speak.

896
00:54:08.698 --> 00:54:11.978
This, uh, talk is certainly open to questions, uh, at either microphone.

897
00:54:14.318 --> 00:54:18.208
So, you know, I was struck and have thought,

898
00:54:18.438 --> 00:54:21.898
I think a lot of people have thought, Ted, about, you know,

899
00:54:22.398 --> 00:54:26.238
the point that you brought up that maybe we don't need to have CAR T-cells

900
00:54:26.298 --> 00:54:30.068
approved. Maybe this can be more like transplant where, you know, these, uh,

