01:10:33.794 --> 01:10:37.564
And so as the populations get smaller, the reflexive thing to do is to charge more

1187
01:10:37.654 --> 01:10:41.224
because of the impact that you're going to have, but that does have a hard ceiling.

1188
01:10:42.594 --> 01:10:46.074
And so to show quantitatively, we have seen an increase in

1189
01:10:46.134 --> 01:10:48.254
biotech venture capital funding

1190
01:10:49.434 --> 01:10:53.194
increase over the past five years, $17 billion to over $21 billion

1191
01:10:53.234 --> 01:10:56.994
between 2020 and 2024, but that has not been distributed

1192
01:10:57.114 --> 01:11:00.454
equally. We've seen a threefold increase in funding for companies focused on

1193
01:11:00.494 --> 01:11:04.394
metabolism, and that's driven primarily by GLP-1s, a nearly

1194
01:11:04.414 --> 01:11:07.614
doubling of funding for companies focused on immunology, and again,

1195
01:11:07.814 --> 01:11:11.394
IL-23 and all the other novel autoimmune drugs, CAR

1196
01:11:11.434 --> 01:11:15.414
T-cells for autoimmune diseases and the like, and a 15%

1197
01:11:15.474 --> 01:11:17.854
decrease in funding for companies focused on oncology.

1198
01:11:17.894 --> 01:11:21.774
And that is a substantial decrease, and that is going to trickle

1199
01:11:21.794 --> 01:11:22.874
through the ecosystem.

1200
01:11:24.554 --> 01:11:27.394
So when we think about why it's hard to get new drugs approved for pediatric

1201
01:11:27.454 --> 01:11:31.394
indications with that as sort of a landscape, I want to break things into three

1202
01:11:31.434 --> 01:11:34.434
different categories because, again, I think we tend to think about this as a

1203
01:11:34.494 --> 01:11:35.194
monolithic

1204
01:11:36.034 --> 01:11:37.114
problem, and it's not.

1205
01:11:38.434 --> 01:11:42.284
There are, as I see, really three categories of how we get

1206
01:11:42.334 --> 01:11:43.664
new drugs to children. One

1207
01:11:44.474 --> 01:11:47.444
is to work with drugs that are in active clinical development.

1208
01:11:47.484 --> 01:11:51.123
And of course, the problem that we face is this very slow pace of initiating

1209
01:11:51.154 --> 01:11:54.244
pediatric trials for drugs that are currently in active development for adult

1210
01:11:54.294 --> 01:11:57.734
indications where there are ways to use that drug for a pediatric

1211
01:11:57.754 --> 01:12:01.383
indication. And I'll talk briefly about some of what I see as insufficient

1212
01:12:01.474 --> 01:12:04.274
financial and regulatory incentives, both on the positive and negative

1213
01:12:04.334 --> 01:12:08.274
side. The second place where we tend to get frustrated is that we

1214
01:12:08.354 --> 01:12:11.974
see drugs that we think could be really important for pediatric

1215
01:12:12.014 --> 01:12:15.894
patients or where we've actually generated evidence of activity for pediatric

1216
01:12:15.934 --> 01:12:19.854
patients, and then those drugs are deprioritized for their adult indications or the

1217
01:12:19.894 --> 01:12:23.784
programs are terminated, and that leaves us feeling super frustrated because

1218
01:12:23.814 --> 01:12:26.674
we know that there's a drug that we think could be useful, but we have no way of

1219
01:12:26.714 --> 01:12:30.254
rescuing it. And I want to talk a little bit about the complexity of actually

1220
01:12:30.294 --> 01:12:34.194
finding that diamond in the rough that ticks all of the boxes, that's investable,

1221
01:12:34.244 --> 01:12:36.054
approvable, and with sufficient patent life.

1222
01:12:36.774 --> 01:12:40.504
And then finally, I'll take just a very brief period of time and talk about some of

1223
01:12:40.534 --> 01:12:44.074
the specific barriers to making drugs that are specific for childhood cancer.

1224
01:12:44.134 --> 01:12:48.074
That is where there's no application for adult indications, and that really has

1225
01:12:48.114 --> 01:12:51.714
to do with the continued high cost and high risk of drug development for small

1226
01:12:51.794 --> 01:12:55.534
populations where new target validation and trial execution remains a challenge.

1227
01:12:56.574 --> 01:12:59.994
So let's talk about trying to move drugs that are currently in development for

1228
01:13:00.054 --> 01:13:03.474
adults. Why are the incentives not working?

1229
01:13:03.524 --> 01:13:07.174
And I would argue if you walk away with anything, it's that the carrots and the

1230
01:13:07.234 --> 01:13:11.154
sticks are simply not big enough. It's not that

1231
01:13:11.194 --> 01:13:14.734
we need more sticks, we just need bigger sticks.

1232
01:13:15.274 --> 01:13:18.694
And it's not that we need more carrots, we just need some bigger carrots.

1233
01:13:18.774 --> 01:13:21.394
The ones that we have actually work,

1234
01:13:22.194 --> 01:13:25.790
but they don't work well enough.Obviously, everybody's aware

1235
01:13:25.810 --> 01:13:29.770
of the drama around the approval or not approval, or renewal

1236
01:13:29.810 --> 01:13:32.510
or non-renewal of the priority review voucher legislation.

1237
01:13:32.570 --> 01:13:36.380
It has been finally, after a gap, renewed, and

1238
01:13:36.410 --> 01:13:40.250
those priority review vouchers as the scarcity of them

1239
01:13:40.290 --> 01:13:43.030
became concerning, the price started to go up.

1240
01:13:43.100 --> 01:13:46.870
And they are still valuable. They can represent $100 million or $150 or

1241
01:13:46.880 --> 01:13:50.690
$200 million. And to a small company, that's a lot of money.

1242
01:13:50.710 --> 01:13:54.330
But we are not able to factor that into our modeling for starting companies who are

1243
01:13:54.350 --> 01:13:58.290
investing in pediatric research because the program is still not

1244
01:13:58.330 --> 01:14:02.230
permanently authorized. It turns out, and I didn't realize this

1245
01:14:02.270 --> 01:14:06.230
until I was preparing for this talk, that the FDA has specifically now asked

1246
01:14:06.250 --> 01:14:09.860
that the program be permanently reauthorized, which is really unusual because they

1247
01:14:09.870 --> 01:14:12.500
weren't a big fan of the program when it initially came out because it made

1248
01:14:12.550 --> 01:14:13.519
everything a priority,

1249
01:14:14.350 --> 01:14:16.450
but they are asking for it to be reauthorized.

1250
01:14:16.510 --> 01:14:20.290
And I think that if we can have that step there, that will be helpful.

1251
01:14:20.410 --> 01:14:24.320
But it's important to remember for large companies that are developing a

1252
01:14:24.350 --> 01:14:28.030
drug for an adult indication, PRVs are only awarded if the

1253
01:14:28.090 --> 01:14:31.440
initial approval is for a pediatric indication.

1254
01:14:32.000 --> 01:14:35.810
They're not awarded for supplemental approval, so you can come in first for ovarian

1255
01:14:35.850 --> 01:14:39.670
cancer. If your next approval is for rhabdomyosarcoma, you do not get the PRV.

1256
01:14:40.390 --> 01:14:44.310
So it's a carrot for small companies who may be able to make that trade-off, or for

1257
01:14:44.320 --> 01:14:47.390
small companies who are developing pediatric-only drugs, but not for large

1258
01:14:47.430 --> 01:14:51.390
companies where the adult market is really the priority.

1259
01:14:51.430 --> 01:14:55.370
And as for the sticks, and by this I mean the pediatric study plans and the Race

1260
01:14:55.410 --> 01:14:56.470
for Children Act and the

1261
01:14:58.470 --> 01:15:02.390
pediatric investigation plans, they have had an impact.

1262
01:15:02.650 --> 01:15:06.410
They have done what they set out to do, increase the number of trial

1263
01:15:06.550 --> 01:15:10.310
starts for pediatric trials using adult cancer

1264
01:15:10.330 --> 01:15:13.630
drugs. That is an intended consequence of that particular stick.

1265
01:15:14.270 --> 01:15:18.050
But as you know, sticks have unintended consequences, and

1266
01:15:18.170 --> 01:15:21.530
one is the fact that we have in industry a

1267
01:15:21.650 --> 01:15:25.330
problem with lots of companies prosecuting the

1268
01:15:25.370 --> 01:15:28.880
exact same target. And what you see in the graph on the left is over

1269
01:15:28.910 --> 01:15:32.340
time, for any given target, the number of

1270
01:15:32.450 --> 01:15:35.790
assets in development for oncology and non-oncology indications.

1271
01:15:35.830 --> 01:15:37.630
And on the right, a breakdown of this.

1272
01:15:37.650 --> 01:15:41.150
This is a little bit old, but I think it's illustrative that in

1273
01:15:41.370 --> 01:15:45.080
2000, we had a large number of targets that we were making

1274
01:15:45.110 --> 01:15:48.210
drugs for, and we had small numbers of companies going after them.

1275
01:15:48.230 --> 01:15:51.410
And that's great to have that kind of redundancy because molecules fail and

1276
01:15:51.430 --> 01:15:55.370
programs fail. But on the right, you can see that once we had

1277
01:15:55.430 --> 01:15:59.370
targets that were well-validated, we had a huge number of companies crowding a

1278
01:15:59.510 --> 01:16:01.910
large number of products into that space, 60

1279
01:16:02.070 --> 01:16:05.950
CD19 drugs in development. Well, that's

1280
01:16:06.650 --> 01:16:10.550
great for adult DLBCL, but the problem is, if you've

1281
01:16:10.590 --> 01:16:14.570
got 60 CD19-directed drugs and

1282
01:16:14.610 --> 01:16:18.150
you only have a couple of hundred patients or three, four,

1283
01:16:18.410 --> 01:16:22.090
500 patients with CD19 positive disease who aren't cured by their initial

1284
01:16:22.110 --> 01:16:24.910
therapy, how are we going to do all of those trials?

1285
01:16:25.490 --> 01:16:28.910
And in the absence of prioritization or global strategy, we face a real

1286
01:16:28.990 --> 01:16:32.690
challenge. How do we find the best new therapies to take

1287
01:16:32.770 --> 01:16:36.650
into a limited number of patients with a fixed and diminishing pool of

1288
01:16:36.730 --> 01:16:37.350
resources?

1289
01:16:39.170 --> 01:16:43.050
So turning to repurposing, people might say, "Well, all right, understand

1290
01:16:43.110 --> 01:16:44.610
that. What about all the drugs on the shelf?

1291
01:16:44.910 --> 01:16:48.710
Shouldn't we be able to take things that are essentially worth nothing and

1292
01:16:48.770 --> 01:16:52.710
create value with them?" So there is a big quote

1293
01:16:52.810 --> 01:16:56.330
shelf, although I will disvalue the notion that there's an actual shelf with

1294
01:16:56.370 --> 01:16:59.650
deprioritized drugs on them. God knows I spent eight years at Day One looking for

1295
01:16:59.710 --> 01:17:03.690
them. There is no shelf. But what you do have is a large number of companies

1296
01:17:03.730 --> 01:17:06.090
that are now trading below their enterprise value.

1297
01:17:06.120 --> 01:17:09.870
And what that means is that for these public companies, the stock

1298
01:17:09.910 --> 01:17:13.810
market values them as being worth less than the amount of cash that

1299
01:17:13.850 --> 01:17:17.230
they have, plus the value of the internal programs, and that makes it very hard for

1300
01:17:17.250 --> 01:17:20.810
these companies to raise. And when they can't raise money, they ultimately go out

1301
01:17:20.850 --> 01:17:22.530
of business and strand their programs.

1302
01:17:23.380 --> 01:17:26.050
So you can buy these programs for very little money.

1303
01:17:26.130 --> 01:17:29.920
The problem is that the return on that investment is a math problem, and

1304
01:17:29.970 --> 01:17:33.790
that math problem is called the treatment addressable market or TAM math problem.

1305
01:17:34.310 --> 01:17:36.710
So if you look at this pie chart on the right, you see

1306
01:17:37.570 --> 01:17:40.810
essentially the breakdown of all childhood cancers by percentage.

1307
01:17:41.009 --> 01:17:44.870
Now, if you just stay with the United States, and we know that there's about

1308
01:17:44.910 --> 01:17:48.890
16,000 new cancer diagnoses per year, all you need to do is

1309
01:17:48.950 --> 01:17:52.040
multiply the smaller wedges in the pie chart here by

1310
01:17:52.050 --> 01:17:55.970
16,000. And if you take into account the fact

1311
01:17:56.010 --> 01:17:59.530
that we probably cure about 50% of patients with standard of care,

1312
01:18:00.270 --> 01:18:04.010
what that means is for anything that's not acute lymphoblastic leukemia or

1313
01:18:04.050 --> 01:18:07.710
low-grade glioma, the treatment addressable market, that is the

1314
01:18:07.750 --> 01:18:11.710
patients who you could actually have eligible for

1315
01:18:12.170 --> 01:18:15.490
treatment with a new drug, falls far below the level sufficient to support

1316
01:18:15.510 --> 01:18:16.850
biopharmaceutical investment.

1317
01:18:18.030 --> 01:18:18.940
And that is

1318
01:18:20.290 --> 01:18:24.240
really a function of something called net present value that

1319
01:18:24.310 --> 01:18:28.090
measures the present value of expected future cash flows with the present

1320
01:18:28.130 --> 01:18:31.950
value of anticipated cash outflows.

1321
01:18:32.360 --> 01:18:35.350
And what this means is that you're going to spend more money developing the drug

1322
01:18:35.390 --> 01:18:39.090
than you will ever possibly make, and that is a very hard thing for

1323
01:18:39.170 --> 01:18:43.070
any investor with a fiduciary obligation to their limited partners to

1324
01:18:43.110 --> 01:18:43.270
do.

1325
01:18:44.430 --> 01:18:48.210
And again, back to Sutro O2, I think that this provides a very important

1326
01:18:48.250 --> 01:18:51.570
lesson. The biology around the CBF-GLIS

1327
01:18:53.770 --> 01:18:55.630
fusion driving folate receptor

1328
01:18:56.490 --> 01:19:00.250
1 expression on AML was remarkable biology, and I thought it was

1329
01:19:00.290 --> 01:19:04.090
brilliant to apply a folate receptor ADC, and clearly, we

1330
01:19:04.190 --> 01:19:06.380
saw evidence of anti-tumor activity.

1331
01:19:07.130 --> 01:19:11.030
But the problem is that at the end of the day, this drug

1332
01:19:11.070 --> 01:19:12.610
was going to be a bridge to transplant.

1333
01:19:12.650 --> 01:19:16.399
And no matter how you slice it and dice it, with a small number of patients getting

1334
01:19:16.430 --> 01:19:19.280
this drug for four or five months or six months tops,

1335
01:19:20.100 --> 01:19:21.930
there's no way that you can make the math work.

1336
01:19:21.970 --> 01:19:23.010
There's no way that the

1337
01:19:24.350 --> 01:19:27.130
commercialization

1338
01:19:28.270 --> 01:19:31.250
potential of this drug was ever going to pay for even the cost of the

1339
01:19:31.270 --> 01:19:34.670
registrational trial, let alone manufacturing the drug in perpetuity for these

1340
01:19:34.710 --> 01:19:38.170
patients. And so we need to find different ways of

1341
01:19:38.210 --> 01:19:41.710
financing drugs for which we cannot commercialize them in a

1342
01:19:41.750 --> 01:19:45.466
traditional model.And you don't have to just take my word for it.

1343
01:19:45.886 --> 01:19:49.846
I'm just a baby VC. Here's a much older VC, and he will tell you

1344
01:19:49.906 --> 01:19:53.746
the same thing that I'm telling you, which is that investors invest in programs and

1345
01:19:53.786 --> 01:19:57.386
not just ideas, and that regardless of whether or not you're asking them for a half

1346
01:19:57.426 --> 01:20:01.316
million dollars, five million dollars or $50 million, those investors are looking

1347
01:20:01.346 --> 01:20:03.406
for a three to five-fold return on their investment.

1348
01:20:03.436 --> 01:20:07.306
And that is just unfortunately a hardcore fact of venture math that we

1349
01:20:07.386 --> 01:20:10.976
need to think about when we think about how we're going to pick the programs that

1350
01:20:10.986 --> 01:20:13.126
we want to invest in for pediatric cancer patients.

1351
01:20:14.076 --> 01:20:17.686
And then finally, with regard to trying to make molecules bespoke to

1352
01:20:17.706 --> 01:20:20.996
pediatric cancers, I think it's important to remind people of the current metrics

1353
01:20:21.006 --> 01:20:24.126
in terms of how well we do when we take a new molecule into the clinic.

1354
01:20:24.606 --> 01:20:27.366
And again, from this remarkable report from the IQVIA

1355
01:20:27.446 --> 01:20:31.146
Institute, they track the success or

1356
01:20:31.186 --> 01:20:34.846
failure rates, depending on which side of the glass you're looking at for drugs

1357
01:20:34.866 --> 01:20:38.336
that enter clinical development from phase one through to approval.

1358
01:20:38.895 --> 01:20:42.686
And you can see that while we get 50% of drugs,

1359
01:20:43.346 --> 01:20:47.286
and this is in the contemporary era, enter phase one and successfully transit phase

1360
01:20:47.346 --> 01:20:51.126
one to phase two, that rate falls to about a third for

1361
01:20:51.146 --> 01:20:54.956
phase two, going to phase three and about 60% going from

1362
01:20:54.966 --> 01:20:58.066
phase three to approval. And most drugs that get to approval manage to get

1363
01:20:58.106 --> 01:21:01.516
approved. But the problem is that when you multiply all these proportions together,

1364
01:21:01.586 --> 01:21:04.926
you come up with a composite success rate of about 7% to

1365
01:21:05.146 --> 01:21:09.126
9%. And that actually gets a further haircut when you

1366
01:21:09.186 --> 01:21:12.746
go and subset this by the mechanism of action.

1367
01:21:12.776 --> 01:21:16.266
And it turns out that we're getting worse, believe it or not, at making

1368
01:21:16.326 --> 01:21:19.976
small molecules get all the way through to approval, much better at

1369
01:21:19.986 --> 01:21:23.236
biologics as well as RNA and oligonucleotide therapies.

1370
01:21:23.696 --> 01:21:27.406
And so when you take the treatment addressable math problem and you multiply it

1371
01:21:27.506 --> 01:21:31.086
by the low probability of success, it makes it even more difficult to justify

1372
01:21:31.146 --> 01:21:33.186
making bespoke drugs for pediatric patients.

1373
01:21:34.186 --> 01:21:37.586
And this valley of death that I'm sure you've all heard about really

1374
01:21:37.646 --> 01:21:38.186
represents,

1375
01:21:39.126 --> 01:21:43.026
I think, in a snapshot, what we need to do to try to fix this.

1376
01:21:43.166 --> 01:21:45.306
We get very excited when we come up with a new target.

1377
01:21:45.346 --> 01:21:48.716
We might get very excited when we have a new molecule that we think has potential

1378
01:21:48.746 --> 01:21:52.056
for pediatric cancer patients, but it is a long and

1379
01:21:52.086 --> 01:21:55.666
expensive path until you get to that value inflection point where you

1380
01:21:55.766 --> 01:21:59.466
show the potential for commercialization, which is really the reward that

1381
01:21:59.546 --> 01:22:02.386
investors are going to get from taking a chance with their investment dollars.

1382
01:22:03.386 --> 01:22:06.906
And even if you do manage to get a drug to clinical trials,

1383
01:22:07.406 --> 01:22:11.396
and this is really the case with SUTRO-002, that's not the end of

1384
01:22:11.446 --> 01:22:15.206
the trek. It's really just the warm-up track for the next

1385
01:22:15.246 --> 01:22:18.846
part of the journey. Because getting to IND or to proof of concept or even to

1386
01:22:18.886 --> 01:22:22.575
approval is just the beginning of a long and expensive process for

1387
01:22:22.626 --> 01:22:25.575
whoever is going to make that drug into a new

1388
01:22:25.626 --> 01:22:29.355
medicine. And that includes things like enduring manufacturing,

1389
01:22:29.946 --> 01:22:33.766
securing supply chain elements, making sure that you have ongoing pharmacovigilance

1390
01:22:33.786 --> 01:22:36.726
and safety reporting, all of which is required by FDA rules,

1391
01:22:38.066 --> 01:22:42.006
physician and patient support, and I can't underestimate the importance

1392
01:22:42.046 --> 01:22:45.686
of medical affairs. Drugs don't sell themselves, and they also

1393
01:22:46.126 --> 01:22:49.946
don't teach physicians how they should be properly used.

1394
01:22:50.386 --> 01:22:53.406
And invariably, there are going to be additional studies required by regulatory

1395
01:22:53.426 --> 01:22:57.286
authorities. In general, whoever takes on a

1396
01:22:57.326 --> 01:23:00.986
drug program has to have the capital required to provide enduring access to

1397
01:23:01.026 --> 01:23:04.826
patients. Any new medicine has to at least pay for its own existence,

1398
01:23:05.126 --> 01:23:07.946
even if they're inexpensive to create or in license.

1399
01:23:08.826 --> 01:23:12.506
And I think a lot of people don't recognize that the back end

1400
01:23:12.566 --> 01:23:15.126
costs of medicines are really significant.

1401
01:23:15.146 --> 01:23:18.526
And this is my experience with toverapnib or OJEMDA now.

1402
01:23:19.206 --> 01:23:23.166
The FIREFLY-1 trial that we use as a basis for getting the drug approved, we

1403
01:23:23.206 --> 01:23:26.986
were able to get that trial up and running and well underway in about

1404
01:23:27.026 --> 01:23:31.006
two years, and we did it with fewer than 50 full-time employees and probably about

1405
01:23:31.346 --> 01:23:33.466
$100 million or so all in.

1406
01:23:34.326 --> 01:23:38.186
But the backside of this, which is getting the drug through to approval, running

1407
01:23:38.306 --> 01:23:42.286
a large 400 patient randomized frontline trial, building out a company,

1408
01:23:42.406 --> 01:23:46.326
medical affairs, commercialization, commercial manufacturing, regulatory, all of

1409
01:23:46.366 --> 01:23:50.276
that took over 150 full-time employees and over $300 million and

1410
01:23:50.326 --> 01:23:54.325
counting because that FIREFLY-2 trial is still ongoing, and most people

1411
01:23:54.366 --> 01:23:57.006
don't see that that investment is really where

1412
01:23:58.266 --> 01:24:00.166
these programs get so expensive.

1413
01:24:01.066 --> 01:24:04.846
So how can we adjust this? We need to find ways of moving

1414
01:24:05.325 --> 01:24:09.226
value inflection points in sooner, generating signals earlier, making sure

1415
01:24:09.266 --> 01:24:13.106
that the things that we invest in are real, and making all of it

1416
01:24:13.166 --> 01:24:17.126
cheaper. And the problem, the interesting paradox is that as discovery gets less

1417
01:24:17.186 --> 01:24:20.656
expensive, we're going to have more things that we can put into this

1418
01:24:20.686 --> 01:24:24.586
pipeline, but the middle parts are still going to be very expensive.

1419
01:24:24.646 --> 01:24:26.886
We don't have a good way of compressing those costs.

1420
01:24:27.926 --> 01:24:31.486
So I want to sort of finish with just some opinions, and it's a sort of chair's

1421
01:24:31.506 --> 01:24:35.426
prerogative that I have the soapbox and I'm going to stand on it right now, that we

1422
01:24:35.506 --> 01:24:38.246
really do need to think a little bit about prioritization.

1423
01:24:38.266 --> 01:24:42.136
And I love this, quote from David Packard of Hewlett Packard, which is that,

1424
01:24:42.366 --> 01:24:46.236
"More organizations die of indigestion than starvation." And I

1425
01:24:46.266 --> 01:24:49.775
think that's really true. I think pediatric oncologists have always been

1426
01:24:49.846 --> 01:24:52.556
afraid of starving for lack of new assets.

1427
01:24:52.586 --> 01:24:56.486
And the problem is, we have a glut of new assets, but we don't know

1428
01:24:56.566 --> 01:24:59.866
how to prioritize them as we try to eat as many of them as we can.

1429
01:24:59.906 --> 01:25:02.606
And the problem is, we have a fixed number of dollars and a fixed number of

1430
01:25:02.666 --> 01:25:06.386
patients, and we are going to potentially die of indigestion here.

1431
01:25:06.506 --> 01:25:10.286
So we need to really manage this fixed

1432
01:25:10.346 --> 01:25:13.286
number of patients and diminishing pool of resources more effectively.

1433
01:25:13.366 --> 01:25:16.766
We have to work together to focus on selecting the very highest

1434
01:25:16.826 --> 01:25:20.086
quality programs that have the highest probability of becoming new

1435
01:25:20.126 --> 01:25:23.766
medicines. We talk about in biotech failing fast or

1436
01:25:23.806 --> 01:25:26.926
failing cheap, and I think that that does need to be reconciled with the

1437
01:25:26.966 --> 01:25:30.636
traditional academic model, which is to dig all the way down to the bottom of the

1438
01:25:30.726 --> 01:25:33.086
problem and not abandon problems halfway through.

1439
01:25:33.646 --> 01:25:36.506
But sometimes when you're dealing with limited resources, you actually have to

1440
01:25:36.546 --> 01:25:37.266
think about that.

1441
01:25:38.566 --> 01:25:40.486
So how do we ultimately reach the promised land?

1442
01:25:40.606 --> 01:25:44.076
I really think that it's essential that we begin talking about really a global

1443
01:25:44.166 --> 01:25:47.294
strategyfor pediatric medicines development.

1444
01:25:47.383 --> 01:25:51.144
And I love this quote from Sun Tzu, which is, "Strategy without tactics is the

1445
01:25:51.314 --> 01:25:55.014
slowest route to victory, and tactics without strategy is the noise

1446
01:25:55.054 --> 01:25:58.624
before defeat." And I think we do really well on tactics.

1447
01:25:59.314 --> 01:26:03.174
But what that means is we run a lot of trials and we generate a lot of data, but we

1448
01:26:03.294 --> 01:26:05.154
still don't know how to get

1449
01:26:05.174 --> 01:26:08.834
those data turned into medicines for

1450
01:26:08.934 --> 01:26:12.674
patients. And we need to have strategy to organize our

1451
01:26:12.714 --> 01:26:16.244
tactics and really help guide us to getting things

1452
01:26:16.354 --> 01:26:20.014
across the goal line, CAR T cells potentially being

1453
01:26:20.034 --> 01:26:23.554
accepted. We have to understand what the goal really is.

1454
01:26:23.674 --> 01:26:26.514
Getting something to proof of concept but not having a path to getting it to

1455
01:26:26.574 --> 01:26:30.384
patients will have the exact same impact as not even getting it to proof of

1456
01:26:30.474 --> 01:26:30.934
concept.

1457
01:26:31.874 --> 01:26:33.614
And sometimes that means waiting.

1458
01:26:33.894 --> 01:26:37.594
It means having a target product profile for the disease, but then

1459
01:26:37.654 --> 01:26:39.694
waiting for the right drug to come along.

1460
01:26:39.754 --> 01:26:42.474
The age of therapeutic innovation is not over, and I think

1461
01:26:42.534 --> 01:26:46.134
my sort of plea to

1462
01:26:46.174 --> 01:26:49.694
pediatric oncologists is to not be afraid that you're going to run out of drugs to

1463
01:26:49.753 --> 01:26:53.714
try. You're not going to run out of new things to try, but maybe wait

1464
01:26:54.154 --> 01:26:55.634
for the right thing to come along.

1465
01:26:56.934 --> 01:26:59.794
And some final thoughts on how to get to our shared goal, I think that working as a

1466
01:26:59.834 --> 01:27:03.134
unified community and treating pediatric cancer drug development as a global

1467
01:27:03.154 --> 01:27:06.914
enterprise is essential. We should be running the trials that we should,

1468
01:27:07.054 --> 01:27:10.494
not the trials that we can, and we need to be ruthlessly efficient here.

1469
01:27:11.094 --> 01:27:14.174
I would also encourage us to consider how the industry is adapting.

1470
01:27:14.294 --> 01:27:18.244
There's a huge move to ex-US trials, including China, as a way

1471
01:27:18.274 --> 01:27:22.174
to not just reduce the cost of development, but to allow us to de-risk programs

1472
01:27:22.214 --> 01:27:25.964
more quickly and efficiently. And that only comes from working together as a global

1473
01:27:26.094 --> 01:27:29.754
coordinated effort. And then finally, and I will say this until

1474
01:27:30.474 --> 01:27:34.074
I reach the end of my days, we have to make sure that every single

1475
01:27:34.174 --> 01:27:38.054
patient's data is captured for real world evidence generation.

1476
01:27:38.194 --> 01:27:41.494
It's a travesty that we don't have a unified system to do that.

1477
01:27:41.514 --> 01:27:45.484
We're only hurting ourselves. We will make our lives so much

1478
01:27:45.554 --> 01:27:49.434
easier if we have high quality real world evidence that will allow us to

1479
01:27:49.454 --> 01:27:53.063
run single arm trials more efficiently for the purpose of regulatory approval.

1480
01:27:53.954 --> 01:27:57.794
And with that, I will pause and thank you for your time, and we'll take questions

1481
01:27:57.834 --> 01:27:58.794
for the entire panel.

